Let = (μ_1, …, μ_n) be a tuple of positive integers. A Hurwitz factorisation of type (g, ) is a tuple (σ_0, σ_1, …, σ_m) of permutations in S_|| such that


  * m = 2g-2+n+c(σ_0), where c(σ_0) denotes the number of cycles in the permutation σ_0;

  * σ_1, …, σ_m are transpositions;

  * the cycles of σ_0 σ_1 ⋯σ_m are labelled 1, 2, …, n such that cycle i has length μ_i; and

  * σ_0, σ_1, …, σ_m generate a transitive subgroup of S_||.

If σ_0 is equal to the identity, then we call the factorisation simple . If σ_0 has cycle type (a, a, …, a), then we call the factorisation a-orbifold . If σ_1, …, σ_m is a monotone sequence of transpositions, then we refer to the factorisation as monotone . Recall that σ_1, …, σ_m is a monotone sequence of transpositions if σ_i = (r_i   s_i) with r_i < s_i for i = 1, 2, …, m and s_1 ≤ s_2 ≤⋯≤ s_m.

